8 variables:

  • MPG (miles per gallon)
  • cylinders
  • engine displacement (cu. inches)
  • horsepower
  • vehicle weight (lbs.)
  • time to accelerate from O to 60 mph (sec.)
  • model year (modulo 100), and

  • origin of car (1. American, 2. European,3. Japanese).

  • Also provided are the car labels (types)

  • Missing data values are marked by series of question marks.

In [12]:
# replace the missing values with median value.
# Note, we do not need to specify the column names below
# every column's missing value is replaced with that column's median respectively  (axis =0 means columnwise)
#rdata = rdata.fillna(rdata.median())

medianFiller = lambda x: x.fillna(x.median())
rdata = rdata.apply(medianFiller,axis=0)

rdata['horsepower'] = rdata['horsepower'].astype('float64')  # converting the hp column from object / string type to float

Split data

In [14]:
# lets build our linear model
# independant variables
X = rdata.drop(['mpg','origin_europe'], axis=1)
# the dependent variable
y = rdata[['mpg']]
In [15]:
# Split X and y into training and test set in 70:30 ratio

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=1)

Adding interaction terms

In [20]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn import linear_model

poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, interaction_only=True)
X_train2 = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test2 = poly.fit_transform(X_test)

poly_clf = linear_model.LinearRegression()

poly_clf.fit(X_train2, y_train)

y_pred = poly_clf.predict(X_test2)

#print(y_pred)

#In sample (training) R^2 will always improve with the number of variables!
print(poly_clf.score(X_train2, y_train))

0.9015975293463855
In [21]:
#Out off sample (testing) R^2 is our measure of sucess and does improve
print(poly_clf.score(X_test2, y_test))

0.8647441061366246
In [22]:
# but this improves as the cost of 29 extra variables!
print(X_train.shape)
print(X_train2.shape)

(278, 8)
(278, 37)
  • Polynomial Features (with only interaction terms) have improved the Out of sample R^2. However at the cost of increaing the number of variables significantly.
